title: For Sale/Trade:  Mossberg 590A1 SPX
location: Wallkill, NY, Hudson Valley, New York
postcontent:
Up for sale or trade is my Mossberg 590A1 SPX. These are as close as you can get to the US Navy issue 590A1’s. The 590A1 is basically a Mossberg 500 pump action shotgun with a few improvements at the request of the US Military. The 590A1 has a thicker walled barrel and receiver and a metal trigger group and safetey (as opposed to the 500’s polymer parts). Think 500 on steroids. The thing is then coated in a special Parkerizing process that makes it very resistant to corrosion (again to Navy specs). This scattergun has a picatinny rail mounted on the receiver for easy adaptation of different sighting systems. It comes with a beefy ghost ring rear sight and an AR style fiber optic front sight. The rear site is fully adjustable. Both the front and rear have protective “ears” like most military firearms. Below the 20” barrel is a 9 shot tube and yes, this shotgun comes with a real M9 bayonet made by Ontario Knife Co. (the same one you are not allowed to have on your AR). The M9 bayonet alone is worth $100. This is one bad shotgun.
All local sales must be conducted in my shop and are subject to an 8% New York State Sales Tax. I am willing to ship to your local FFL after payment has cleared. Buyer pays actual shipping costs. Please feel free to ask for additional photos or descriptions. Please ask all questions ahead of time as all sales are final. All trades will be considered, let me know what you have. I may politely decline or we may strike a deal. I am particularly interested in early lever action rifles, early single action revolvers, military firearms, 1911’s, Smith & Wesson and Colt double action revolvers, reloading equipment, tools, jeep parts and recreational vehicles.

postcontent:
For sale is my Beretta 92FS. I bought this pistol about 6 years ago to shoot production class IPSC. It has since been replaced by a Glock 17, and has been riding a slot in my gun safe for quite some time. I shot only a handful of competitions with the weapon, and it was cleaned diligently after each use. I would rate the pistol at 98-99 percent. Minor holster wear on the very tip, and normal barrel blueing wear from the weapon cycling. 

The Beretta comes with 5 magazines. The good, Beretta factory magazines that cost an arm and a leg, not the B/S Army aftermarket ones. That's enough magazines to get one started in competition shooting if they desire. 

Also comes with two concealed carry holsters. A Don Hume H715 IWB and a CQC Holster by BLACKHAWK! designed for the 5-6 o'clock/small of back position. 

Sorry, no box or paperwork that I can find. I'm pretty sure this came in the older cardboard boxes that I didn't feel like storing long term. 

$625... It's coming with over 100 dollars in magazines and holsters, so it's a fair price. It's hard to find one of these new for under $600 with only 2 magazines. If you make an offer, don't insult me or yourself. If it's reasonable (think highest bidder), I'll consider it. 

As always, local laws apply. I must collect a Pistol Purchase Permit, and I'll want you to sign a bill of sale. If you have a concealed carry permit, I will need to see it to make sure it is current, and I will write your permit number on my bill of sale.

title: For Sale:  Beware Ads For Hi Cap Magazines.
postcontent:
I've seen a number of ads lately illegally selling magazines.  Remember folks, it's no longer legal in Colorado to buy, sell, or trade magazines with capacities over 15 rounds.

It's possible the people placing these ads have been living in caves and are completely clueless about the new magazine law.  

It's also possible the ads are being placed by law enforcement looking to make examples of a few buyers who disregard the new law, or by newspaper/TV reporters wanting to make a story on how this law should be better enforced.  

So just be careful.  Don't be the dupe who gets suckered in by cops or reporters.

title: For Sale:  ALL RPIVATE SALES FEES 35 DOLLARS MAX its the law!!!!!!!!!!!!!!
location: ALL OF CALIFORNIA READ THIS, California, United States
postcontent:
Stop getting raped by prices from greedy ass FFL dealers

http://oag.ca.gov/firearms/pubfaqs#14

I want to sell a gun to another person, i.e., a private party transfer. Am I required to conduct the transaction through a licensed California firearms dealer?
Yes. Firearm sales must be conducted through a fully licensed California firearms dealer. Failure to do so is a violation of California law. The buyer (and seller, in the event that the; buyer is denied), must meet the normal firearm purchase and delivery requirements. "Antique firearms," as defined in Section 921(a)(16) of Title 18 of the United States Code, and curio or relic rifles/shotguns, defined in Section 178.11 of Title 27 of the Code of Federal Regulations that are over 50 years old, are exempt from this requirement.

Firearms dealers are required to process private party transfers upon request. Firearms dealers may charge a fee not to exceed $10 per firearm for conducting a private party transfer. Example:

For a private party transfer involving one or more handguns, the total allowable fees, including the DROS, safety, and dealer transfer fees, are not to exceed $35.00 for the first handgun and $31.00 for each additional handgun involved in the same transaction.
For private party transfers involving one or more long guns, or a private party transfer involving one handgun, the total allowable fees, including the DROS, safety, and dealer transfer fees, are not to exceed $35.00. The dealer may charge an additional dealer-service fee of$10.00 per each additional firearm transferred.
(PC section 12072(d))
